3
00:00:09,950 --> 00:00:12,431
Thanks, everybody, for coming over,

4
00:00:12,431 --> 00:00:15,673
and we're really grateful that GDC had us

5
00:00:15,673 --> 00:00:18,875
and allowed us to come and do this talk for you guys.

6
00:00:18,875 --> 00:00:21,956
We did Watch Dogs, and we shipped it about a year ago,

7
00:00:21,956 --> 00:00:24,097
and we're really glad we can talk to you about

8
00:00:24,097 --> 00:00:25,918
a bit more about the music system

9
00:00:25,918 --> 00:00:27,579
and everything that's music in the game

10
00:00:27,579 --> 00:00:28,940
and how that came about for the game.

11
00:00:30,393 --> 00:00:33,495
I'm Olivier Girard, I'm the audio director on the project.

12
00:00:33,495 --> 00:00:37,659
I'm Pavel Maximichev, and I'm the audio designer and the

13
00:00:37,659 --> 00:00:38,680
composer for the game.

14
00:00:39,458 --> 00:00:41,379
So essentially, we wanted to do a talk

15
00:00:41,379 --> 00:00:44,181
that covered the whole aspect of audio on Watch Dogs.

16
00:00:44,181 --> 00:00:45,541
And we started writing it, and we figured

17
00:00:45,541 --> 00:00:47,382
that was way too much stuff to talk about.

18
00:00:47,382 --> 00:00:48,483
So we decided to figure it.

19
00:00:48,483 --> 00:00:52,545
We figured we'll stick to music, which is what proved to be

20
00:00:52,545 --> 00:00:54,086
the most challenging thing for us

21
00:00:54,086 --> 00:00:56,668
as we had to, you know, reconcile the open world

22
00:00:56,668 --> 00:00:58,569
with our own creative objectives

23
00:00:58,569 --> 00:01:00,190
we're gonna get to in about a second.

24
00:01:00,190 --> 00:01:03,732
What we knew from the get-go, we got on Watch Dogs

25
00:01:03,732 --> 00:01:06,713
just when we finished SpinnerCell Conviction

26
00:01:06,713 --> 00:01:07,914
about 5 1â„2 years ago.

27
00:01:07,914 --> 00:01:08,154
And...

28
00:01:09,195 --> 00:01:12,537
all we knew at the time, Watch Dogs was becoming its own thing, was we were

29
00:01:12,537 --> 00:01:16,380
establishing a new brand, and all we knew was a Serious Stone open world game

30
00:01:16,380 --> 00:01:19,222
focused on hacking and the concern raised by technology and all that.

31
00:01:19,222 --> 00:01:24,946
So, Serious Stone was basically all we got, you know, as a major direction from the game.

32
00:01:24,946 --> 00:01:28,428
And that's going to be reflected throughout the whole presentation, because that's

33
00:01:28,428 --> 00:01:29,749
the one thing we kept grabbing onto,

34
00:01:29,749 --> 00:01:32,051
you know, we want to do a Serious Stone thing.

35
00:01:32,051 --> 00:01:35,753
Obviously, you know, doing open world games with a lot of driving and shooting.

36
00:01:35,993 --> 00:01:38,556
uh... there's a lot of of of other

37
00:01:38,556 --> 00:01:42,020
games happening at the same time and some are humorous some are goofy and all that

38
00:01:42,020 --> 00:01:42,420
and I think

39
00:01:42,420 --> 00:01:45,584
that was our way of trying to be different it was you know trying to stick

40
00:01:45,584 --> 00:01:46,325
to that serious tone.

41
00:01:47,569 --> 00:01:53,032
It was a long development cycle and it was the first time for us to actually be part of the pre-production phase.

42
00:01:53,032 --> 00:01:58,976
I'd been at Ubi for a while and had done a lot of crunches, a lot of production phases, but never in pre-production.

43
00:01:58,976 --> 00:02:07,021
So that was a bit uneasy at first, getting into that rhythm of not actually always wrestling with tasks and all that to be doing,

44
00:02:07,021 --> 00:02:12,184
but having deeper thoughts about the whole creative direction and the sound direction of the game.

45
00:02:13,283 --> 00:02:15,524
Also, it was a very large team.

46
00:02:15,524 --> 00:02:19,487
I was used to working with five, six people maximum on a project.

47
00:02:19,487 --> 00:02:23,890
And then we got on Watch Dogs, and eventually we were, you know, this team working just

48
00:02:23,890 --> 00:02:24,290
in Montreal.

49
00:02:24,290 --> 00:02:27,572
And we had other friends as well working in the Paris studios.

50
00:02:27,572 --> 00:02:30,874
We had friends in Newcastle, and we had people in Quebec City all working on sound.

51
00:02:30,874 --> 00:02:35,077
And I think the guys at the Star Control talk...

52
00:02:35,837 --> 00:02:36,778
said it best yesterday.

53
00:02:36,778 --> 00:02:38,438
They said, you know, they embraced standing

54
00:02:38,438 --> 00:02:40,959
on the shoulder of giants, of other people.

55
00:02:40,959 --> 00:02:42,280
And that's pretty much what we're doing here.

56
00:02:42,280 --> 00:02:43,760
I mean, we get to be here today

57
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:46,402
because all these people worked really hard on the game,

58
00:02:46,402 --> 00:02:48,402
and we wouldn't be here without them.

59
00:02:48,402 --> 00:02:51,304
We needed that many people just to ship the game

60
00:02:51,304 --> 00:02:52,764
in the state we wanted it to be.

61
00:02:52,764 --> 00:02:54,625
So we're really grateful about that.

62
00:02:54,625 --> 00:02:56,045
And also the relationship we had

63
00:02:56,045 --> 00:02:58,206
with our creative director, Jonathan Morin,

64
00:02:58,206 --> 00:03:00,067
and our producer, Dominique Guay,

65
00:03:00,067 --> 00:03:02,888
who really enabled us to, you know, achieve our goals

66
00:03:02,888 --> 00:03:04,829
and really reach as far as we could.

67
00:03:05,009 --> 00:03:06,491
with this brand-new IP.

68
00:03:06,491 --> 00:03:08,073
So we're really grateful about that as well.

69
00:03:08,073 --> 00:03:11,737
So as I said about the audio direction,

70
00:03:11,737 --> 00:03:13,979
uh, you know, it wasn't like we came on board

71
00:03:13,979 --> 00:03:15,341
the project five and a half years ago

72
00:03:15,341 --> 00:03:16,602
and said, oh, this is what it's gonna be.

73
00:03:16,602 --> 00:03:18,945
It was, uh, there was a lot of iterations,

74
00:03:18,945 --> 00:03:21,027
obviously because, you know, the game was finding itself.

75
00:03:21,027 --> 00:03:22,629
We were trying to define what we were gonna be.

76
00:03:22,629 --> 00:03:23,911
And we were trying to, you know...

77
00:03:25,212 --> 00:03:27,413
get in sync with what the creative direction was doing,

78
00:03:27,413 --> 00:03:30,335
what the game designers were doing and all that.

79
00:03:30,335 --> 00:03:32,957
But what was really, really important for us on Wazhogs,

80
00:03:32,957 --> 00:03:34,979
and another thing we're really grateful about,

81
00:03:34,979 --> 00:03:38,581
is we had full control and full authority over sound.

82
00:03:38,581 --> 00:03:42,944
It might not be so obvious when, you know, you don't have it,

83
00:03:42,944 --> 00:03:44,465
but to get that on a project...

84
00:03:45,065 --> 00:03:47,386
is really important because we get to push our ideas,

85
00:03:47,386 --> 00:03:49,967
and then we get to sell them to the creative director,

86
00:03:49,967 --> 00:03:51,968
and they can buy in or not into this,

87
00:03:51,968 --> 00:03:53,709
but at least it comes from us.

88
00:03:53,709 --> 00:03:56,290
It's a, you know, bottoms-up perspective on things,

89
00:03:56,290 --> 00:03:58,431
whereas other times, you'll be on a different project,

90
00:03:58,431 --> 00:04:00,752
and the creative vision is gonna be so strong

91
00:04:00,752 --> 00:04:03,073
that you'll become a service to that creative vision.

92
00:04:03,073 --> 00:04:05,914
On Watch Dogs, we really were given a lot of, um...

93
00:04:06,972 --> 00:04:13,079
of room to define ourselves what we wanted this game to be about from an audio perspective

94
00:04:13,079 --> 00:04:16,784
and that really helped us define exactly what Watch Dogs was about.

95
00:04:17,905 --> 00:04:19,826
And what it was about, basically, as I said,

96
00:04:19,826 --> 00:04:22,828
we were just coming off of Spinner Cell Conviction,

97
00:04:22,828 --> 00:04:25,349
and we'd done a lot of interactive music,

98
00:04:25,349 --> 00:04:27,451
but also music that reacted really closely

99
00:04:27,451 --> 00:04:28,812
to what the action was.

100
00:04:28,812 --> 00:04:31,073
And we really, really enjoyed doing that

101
00:04:31,073 --> 00:04:33,114
with the systems for Spinner Cell.

102
00:04:33,114 --> 00:04:35,896
And we decided, well, now we're doing an open world game,

103
00:04:35,896 --> 00:04:38,898
so in theory, this wouldn't be the best approach.

104
00:04:38,898 --> 00:04:41,199
But we decided to challenge ourselves a bit and say,

105
00:04:41,199 --> 00:04:44,141
how can we make the most tailor-made music

106
00:04:44,141 --> 00:04:46,203
for all these moments the player is gonna live?

107
00:04:46,943 --> 00:04:50,966
but still try to make it work with a total freedom promise of the open world.

108
00:04:50,966 --> 00:04:54,369
So that was basically the challenge we put ourselves through

109
00:04:54,369 --> 00:04:56,070
because we really, really enjoyed those moments.

110
00:04:56,070 --> 00:04:58,052
And we said, you know, this is the best way to get, you know,

111
00:04:58,052 --> 00:05:00,174
the maximum emotional impact of the game

112
00:05:00,174 --> 00:05:04,257
is to support these moments with as close a soundtrack as we can have

113
00:05:04,257 --> 00:05:06,498
that reacts to what the player is actually doing.

114
00:05:06,498 --> 00:05:09,281
So, you know, if we realize that the player is, you know,

115
00:05:09,281 --> 00:05:12,163
taking a car and crashing through windows, then can we...

116
00:05:12,884 --> 00:05:16,450
find a way to note that, and can we see that,

117
00:05:16,450 --> 00:05:18,433
and can we support the music?

118
00:05:18,433 --> 00:05:20,617
Can the music support those actions?

119
00:05:20,617 --> 00:05:22,700
I'm not saying this is what we did in the end,

120
00:05:22,700 --> 00:05:24,564
but that was our reasoning from the beginning.

121
00:05:24,564 --> 00:05:26,086
This is what we were trying to achieve.

122
00:05:27,017 --> 00:05:29,720
minimal systems and more mission-based custom tracks.

123
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:32,662
Obviously, we couldn't get, you know, too far away from systems

124
00:05:32,662 --> 00:05:35,925
because the open world still demanded a lot of feedback

125
00:05:35,925 --> 00:05:38,007
and still demanded a lot of attention

126
00:05:38,007 --> 00:05:41,070
because gameplay was kind of king on Watch Dogs

127
00:05:41,070 --> 00:05:42,732
and we wanted to be sure that the gameplay

128
00:05:42,732 --> 00:05:44,913
was getting all the feedbacks it needed.

129
00:05:44,913 --> 00:05:47,075
And a lot of times, a lot of what was happening in the game,

130
00:05:47,075 --> 00:05:48,717
like the vigilante system and all that,

131
00:05:49,117 --> 00:05:52,859
was very subtle and since you know our character didn't necessarily have a

132
00:05:52,859 --> 00:05:55,080
a spider sense thing or whatnot

133
00:05:55,080 --> 00:05:58,241
oftentimes the the solution to those problems how to bring the players

134
00:05:58,241 --> 00:05:59,542
attention to something that's going on

135
00:05:59,542 --> 00:06:02,083
you know very far away down the street

136
00:06:02,083 --> 00:06:05,904
was to change the music or have a specific cue play at a specific time

137
00:06:05,904 --> 00:06:08,926
or when the the police were chasing you and all that so

138
00:06:08,926 --> 00:06:12,447
a lot of the times you know we we did need those systems to be there

139
00:06:12,447 --> 00:06:15,248
just so we could have the proper gameplay feedback for the player so

140
00:06:15,248 --> 00:06:16,529
obviously that created

141
00:06:16,709 --> 00:06:19,973
uh... you know if we have a few conflicts in the game and you know how

142
00:06:19,973 --> 00:06:20,673
we resolve them

143
00:06:20,673 --> 00:06:23,957
is is pretty much you know the the meat and potatoes of this talk

144
00:06:25,674 --> 00:06:32,756
So reconciling all these systems obviously there was technical concerns as well because we couldn't have you know 11 streams of music playing all the same time

145
00:06:32,756 --> 00:06:38,277
Technically we would have gotten a lot of angry engine programmers at our desk if we'd attempted that

146
00:06:38,277 --> 00:06:45,178
And also we were doing a cross gen game which implied that you know however far we would push with the next-gen technology

147
00:06:45,178 --> 00:06:50,039
The current gen guys would hate us that much more so we still want to be friends with them

148
00:06:50,039 --> 00:06:53,780
So you know we try to find a common ground that everybody was happy with what we were doing

149
00:06:54,140 --> 00:06:55,380
but also from a technical perspective,

150
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:57,021
there's just so many stuff you can cram

151
00:06:57,021 --> 00:06:58,823
at the same time through the streams.

152
00:06:58,823 --> 00:07:01,004
We had a lot of readability concerns as well

153
00:07:01,004 --> 00:07:02,985
because it, you know, we could have a lot,

154
00:07:02,985 --> 00:07:04,786
you know, a guy with a boom box

155
00:07:04,786 --> 00:07:06,307
and then you're in your car with your own radio

156
00:07:06,307 --> 00:07:08,328
and then there's mission music playing on top

157
00:07:08,328 --> 00:07:10,830
and that just creates a mess of music really.

158
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:13,331
And if you have, you know, music everywhere,

159
00:07:13,331 --> 00:07:14,352
then you get to the next point,

160
00:07:14,352 --> 00:07:15,532
which is the density concern.

161
00:07:15,532 --> 00:07:17,394
If you got music playing all the time,

162
00:07:17,394 --> 00:07:18,774
the next time it comes in,

163
00:07:18,774 --> 00:07:20,435
it kind of loses its impact a bit.

164
00:07:20,435 --> 00:07:21,476
So, you know, we wanted to be sure

165
00:07:21,476 --> 00:07:23,277
that there's also some times where there's no music.

166
00:07:23,697 --> 00:07:25,778
Or the player can choose to have new music,

167
00:07:25,778 --> 00:07:28,819
so when it comes back in, then it actually means something.

168
00:07:28,819 --> 00:07:32,420
And also, the open world promise, obviously,

169
00:07:32,420 --> 00:07:34,901
was the main thing that we always had to keep in mind.

170
00:07:34,901 --> 00:07:38,283
Because every time we thought we had a good idea,

171
00:07:38,283 --> 00:07:39,883
suddenly we switched our brain to QA mode.

172
00:07:39,883 --> 00:07:42,024
And we're like, so what happens if the player decides

173
00:07:42,024 --> 00:07:45,665
to take an ambulance and drive backwards through the store

174
00:07:45,665 --> 00:07:46,906
as people are calling the police?

175
00:07:46,906 --> 00:07:47,746
Is that still going to work?

176
00:07:47,746 --> 00:07:49,907
And most often, that answer would be no.

177
00:07:49,907 --> 00:07:51,948
And we would have to find another solution.

178
00:07:52,368 --> 00:07:57,431
But that's everything, you know, that's setting the table for the project for the next four years we had to do.

179
00:07:57,431 --> 00:08:00,614
And the first casualty of that was the Muse ambient system.

180
00:08:00,614 --> 00:08:03,496
When we started thinking about Watch Dogs, we knew it was a serious game,

181
00:08:03,496 --> 00:08:07,558
and we knew it was an open world, so we started thinking about our favorite references,

182
00:08:07,558 --> 00:08:10,260
and when that came up was obviously Fallout.

183
00:08:10,680 --> 00:08:12,682
And so we played a lot of Fallout,

184
00:08:12,682 --> 00:08:14,984
and we're like, oh, wow, this game really nails,

185
00:08:14,984 --> 00:08:17,046
you know, selling the Fallout universe

186
00:08:17,046 --> 00:08:20,689
through music and through those small musical cues

187
00:08:20,689 --> 00:08:22,290
that come in and out of the environment.

188
00:08:22,290 --> 00:08:23,091
They're not pieces.

189
00:08:23,091 --> 00:08:24,632
They're just small musical phrases

190
00:08:24,632 --> 00:08:25,012
that come in and out.

191
00:08:25,012 --> 00:08:27,114
I'm like, this is brilliant. Let's try that.

192
00:08:27,114 --> 00:08:29,436
So we had our composer make a bunch of these things,

193
00:08:29,436 --> 00:08:31,978
and we had, you know, a bunch of them

194
00:08:31,978 --> 00:08:33,019
for every act of the game,

195
00:08:33,019 --> 00:08:35,701
and we were super happy with the system.

196
00:08:35,701 --> 00:08:38,283
And then it hit us, once everything was in place,

197
00:08:38,283 --> 00:08:39,424
that, you know, a...

198
00:08:40,565 --> 00:08:43,047
a dense, living Chicago,

199
00:08:43,047 --> 00:08:46,609
is not the same audio landscape at all as the wasteland.

200
00:08:46,609 --> 00:08:48,110
So there's much less room in the mix

201
00:08:48,110 --> 00:08:50,212
for these small, subtle things to come in.

202
00:08:50,212 --> 00:08:52,113
And obviously, we reached that density concern as well,

203
00:08:52,113 --> 00:08:54,955
where there was always some kind of music playing at the same time.

204
00:08:54,955 --> 00:08:57,857
So we said, all right, let's take all these very expensive things we bought

205
00:08:57,857 --> 00:08:59,498
and put them aside for now

206
00:08:59,498 --> 00:09:02,721
and see if we can do something else with them later on.

207
00:09:02,721 --> 00:09:05,783
So we, you know, we learned a hard lesson right there.

208
00:09:05,783 --> 00:09:09,025
This is an example of these small musical phrases we had.

209
00:09:35,227 --> 00:09:38,849
So really the objective there was really let's sell the flavor of the game.

210
00:09:38,849 --> 00:09:42,372
Let's say this is Watch Dogs, this is new, this is a serious game.

211
00:09:42,372 --> 00:09:45,354
So hopefully that's what you got from this small piece.

212
00:09:45,354 --> 00:09:48,657
But that was the direction we were going for.

213
00:09:48,657 --> 00:09:49,298
Obviously.

214
00:09:49,698 --> 00:09:53,081
conflicts, many systems trying to fight at the same time.

215
00:09:53,081 --> 00:09:55,643
And we had to make sure all those systems existed together

216
00:09:55,643 --> 00:09:57,244
and the system was smart enough to realize

217
00:09:57,244 --> 00:09:58,505
when there should be a transition.

218
00:09:58,505 --> 00:10:01,668
So what you see here is our glorious music tree,

219
00:10:01,668 --> 00:10:04,010
which was made by our programmers in Montreal,

220
00:10:04,010 --> 00:10:06,832
which basically looks at the game and sees,

221
00:10:06,832 --> 00:10:08,493
well, what part of the game am I in?

222
00:10:08,493 --> 00:10:09,314
Is this the first act?

223
00:10:09,314 --> 00:10:11,836
Is this the later act of the game?

224
00:10:11,836 --> 00:10:14,358
Maybe what kind of, what district am I in?

225
00:10:14,358 --> 00:10:15,819
Or am I in a mission?

226
00:10:15,819 --> 00:10:16,400
Am I not in a mission?

227
00:10:16,400 --> 00:10:18,081
Is the police chasing me?

228
00:10:18,081 --> 00:10:19,362
Is there a vigilante of it going on?

229
00:10:19,622 --> 00:10:20,903
And there's a whole bunch of priorities

230
00:10:20,903 --> 00:10:22,343
within all those systems.

231
00:10:22,343 --> 00:10:23,884
And this is basically the overall,

232
00:10:23,884 --> 00:10:24,784
I'd say, music system.

233
00:10:24,784 --> 00:10:27,605
Because once you get into an actual mission of the game,

234
00:10:27,605 --> 00:10:29,285
then this is kind of overruled.

235
00:10:29,285 --> 00:10:32,026
And then the music, the missions actually take over,

236
00:10:32,026 --> 00:10:33,747
and they have their own music conditions

237
00:10:33,747 --> 00:10:35,147
that are set through scripts.

238
00:10:35,147 --> 00:10:37,788
So let's say a mission had you, uh, obviously,

239
00:10:37,788 --> 00:10:39,228
from, uh, let's say...

240
00:10:39,368 --> 00:10:41,369
pick apples because that's very watchdogs.

241
00:10:41,369 --> 00:10:43,830
But let's say a mission had you pick apples in an orchard,

242
00:10:43,830 --> 00:10:45,351
then maybe we would try to hook ourselves up

243
00:10:45,351 --> 00:10:47,072
to the amount of apple in your basket,

244
00:10:47,072 --> 00:10:49,292
and then the music would fluctuate around that.

245
00:10:49,292 --> 00:10:50,813
